english:
  title: Lodging at Boryeong County
  author: Yu Seung-dan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I departed Haepung in daylight,
    Reaching Boryeong as night fell.
    Wind through the bamboo startles my sleep,
    Clouds weep—rain blocks the road ahead.
    Evening mist weighs heavy upon my head,
    Morning sun briefly lifts the burden from my bones.
    Now I understand: this aging, afflicted frame
    Can only divine the weather—clearing or gathering clouds.
  footnotes:
    - Haepung (海豐) and Boryeong (保寧) are place names in classical Korea. The poet's journey from one to the other frames the overnight stay that becomes a meditation on aging and mortality.
    - The final couplet employs divination imagery—traditionally used to predict external fortune—as a metaphor for the body's helpless dependence on circumstance, suggesting that age reduces human agency to mere passive observation.
